article.description: LSU's Temeka Johnson had blurred vision and a concussion after a win over UW-Green Bay.
article.headline: LSU doesn't miss a beat after losing Johnson
article.linkText: LSU fights through injury to top Wisconsin-Green Bay
article.story:
EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- The LSU Lady Tigers stayed calm and focused
after watching teammate Temeka Johnson crumble to the floor, crying
in pain.

	   Without saying a word, the Lady Tigers did what they had to do:
They succeeded in holding off surprisingly resilient Wisconsin
Green-Bay 80-69 in the second round of the West Regional on Monday
night.

	   The Lady Tigers (29-3) advance to the round of 16 for the first
time since 2000. In Palo Alto, Calif., they'll face the winner of
Tuesday's game between Louisiana Tech and Ohio State in Ruston, La.

	   But the cost was great. Johnson, the SEC tournament's most
valuable player, had blurred vision and a slight concussion. Her
future in the tournament is uncertain.

	   "Anytime you lose a player of that caliber, someone has to step
up,'' said Doneeka Hodges, who led the Lady Tigers with 20 points.
"We didn't really have to say anything, we just knew we had to
keep playing.''

	   Chandra Johnson had a career-high 29 points for eighth-seeded
Wisconsin-Green Bay (28-4), which had won 12 straight dating to
Jan. 25 -- including a first-round victory against Washington.

	   The tenacious Phoenix, who trailed by as many as 13 points in
the first half, came out with renewed energy in the second and
squeezed the margin to 48-43 on Sara Boyer's jumper with 12:58
left.
	   Green Bay threatened again when Kristy Loiselle nailed a 3, and
Johnson added a jumper to make it 59-54. But the Phoenix couldn't
get any closer.

	   "We were in the game. Regardless of what happened we were in
the game,'' Phoenix coach Kevin Borseth said. "We were very, very
close to shocking them.''

	   As Wisconsin Green Bay made its second-half push, Temeka Johnson
was hit in the head after fouling Chandra Johnson.

	   Temeka Johnson remained on the floor for several moments before
heading to the locker room with the help of a trainer. She later
returned briefly to the game but quickly went back to the bench
where she kept ice pressed to her head.

	   She was replaced admirably by senior reserve Kisha James, who
finished with five points and four assists in a solid 15 minutes.

	   "Was she not terrific? Absolutely terrific. She came to play,''
LSU coach Sue Gunter said. "It was her time to shine, and she
did.''

	   The Phoenix trailed most of the first half but came within 25-22
on Chandra Johnson's jumper with 7:25 to go.

	   The accurate Lady Tigers quickly pulled back out to a 35-24 lead
and were up 43-31 at the half. LSU made 20 of 26 shots from the
field in the first half and Wisconsin-Green Bay simply couldn't
keep up.

	   The Phoenix, who earned an automatic NCAA bid by claiming the
Horizon League tournament championship, earned their first victory
in five tournament appearances with the win over the Huskies. The
school's first NCAA win was a goal Borseth set for the Phoenix this
season. Anything else, he said earlier, was "icing on the cake.''

	   "They made a believer out of me,'' Gunter said. "Kevin just
does a great job with them. They're very disciplined and they're so
hard to get out of their system.''

	   The Lady Tigers routed Southwest Texas 86-50 for their
sixth-straight first-round victory.

	   The Lady Tigers lost to just three teams during the regular
season -- Arkansas, Vanderbilt and Tennessee -- then beat all three
in the SEC tournament to finish the regular season ranked No. 3.
